{"type":"message","id":"db1ef488","parentId":"4cf6d19e","timestamp":"2026-04-15T06:16:17.832Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The memory search returned \"disabled: true\" - the heartbeat-state.json is not accessible via memory. But I can see from the session messages that the last known state was stored. Let me look at the previous cycles' system messages to extract the last known state.\n\nFrom the system messages in `agent:main` session (session `bca9bbb9-d1eb-408d-9e3d-14dd521dcc45`), the last known state comparisons were:\n- 05:18 UTC: cron:ed2d0b5d вњ… cron:e7885813 вњ… cron:6f3323ef вњ…\n- Throughout the morning: same 3 crons running, no changes\n\n\n- Latest confirmed state: 06:09 UTC - same 3 crons running\n\nNow I'm checking what's actually changed between the last report at 06:09 UTC and the current time at 06:15 UTC. The three main cron jobs are still active with no new sessions spawned and no failures reported, though there's mention of a session that was still running at 06:09 UTC.\n\nLooking more carefully at the session data, the `agent:main` session did complete normally around 06:09 UTC as expected, so that's not a change either. The subagents from the parent cron are showing as done, but they were already completed in the previous cycle. Comparing against the baseline of 06:03 UTC, the main session transition from running to done appears to be the only actual state change I can identify.\n\nWait, but the previous cycle at 06:13 UTC already reported that `agent:main` had completed, so this is just confirming the same state. The active sessions remain the three cron jobs still running, with no new failures, no new blockers, and the pre-existing orphaned cron jobs still there. Nothing has actually changed from what was already reported.\n\nSince the system is stable with no new activity, I'm staying silent as instructed.","thinkingSignature":"9aa7a6a6067e20252ae90a077ab060e6839bb0c2a3a1be3f3e866079187a428f"},{